			<h4><a rel="nofollow" id="comment_link_65478052" name="comment_link_65478052" href="//tech.slashdot.org/comments.pl?sid=23728266&amp;cid=65478052" onclick="return D2.setFocusComment(65478052)" >Re:</a>


		 	<span id="comment_score_65478052" class="score"> (<a href="#" onclick="getModalPrefs('modcommentlog', 'Moderation Comment Log', 65478052); return false"><span class=opt>Score:</span>2</a>)</span></h4>
		</div>
		<div class="details">
			<span class="by"><span class="byby">by </span><a rel="nofollow" href="//slashdot.org/~allo">allo</a>  <span class="uid"><a rel="nofollow" href="//slashdot.org/~allo">( 1728082 )</a></span></a></span><span class="writes" style="display:none"> writes:</span> 
			<span class="otherdetails" id="comment_otherdetails_65478052"></span>
		</div>
	</div>
	<div class="commentBody">
		<div id="comment_body_65478052"><p>The point is, that there is not "store into the model" step.</p><p>The training gets an input and an expected output and then computes how large the error between expected and actual output is. Afterward it updates the weights using the derivatives of the error, not the input or expected output texts.<br>The only way to "store" something in a model is overfitting, and the pigeon hole principle tells that you can only overfit a small amount of training material.</p></div>
	</div>

	<div class="commentSub" id="comment_sub_65478052">

</div>
